\par \pard\plain \s24\sb0\sa283{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Structures in the EITE Language }
\par \pard\plain \s24\sb0\sa283{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The EITE Language uses the following main types of entity to represent information: }
\par \pard\plain \s35\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Type}
\par \pard\plain \s36\li567\ri0\lin567\rin0\fi0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Types are templates describing the structure of objects. They are known as prototypes or classes in most programming languages, depending on whether objects described by them inherit changes to the types made after the object was created. (Objects can be used as types by casting.) Type names begin with a capital letter when in source form. }
\par \pard\plain \s35\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Object}
\par \pard\plain \s36\li567\ri0\lin567\rin0\fi0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
An object is an entity that conforms to a given type (an }{\cs19\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
instance}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 of that type). The most general type is }{\cs19\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
object}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
, and there is no need for an object to conform to any other type. Whether the type it inherits from is treated as a class or a prototype should be able to be specified. }
\par \pard\plain \s35\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Block}
\par \pard\plain \s36\li567\ri0\lin567\rin0\fi0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
A block is a group of statements. }
\par \pard\plain \s35\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Project}
\par \pard\plain \s36\li567\ri0\lin567\rin0\fi0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
A project is a single document, and if relevant, any other documents maintained as part of that document. }
\par \pard\plain \s35\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Module}
\par \pard\plain \s36\li567\ri0\lin567\rin0\fi0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
A module is one or more Library-mode documents that have a package name for addressing the things they provide. }
\par \pard\plain \s35\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
List}
\par \pard\plain \s36\li567\ri0\lin567\rin0\fi0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
A list is an ordered list of objects.}{
{\*\atnid }{\*\atnauthor }\chatn{\*\annotation{\*\atndate 1736006903}\ltrpar\rtlch \ltrch\loch{\langfe1023\alang1023\dbch\af11\dbch\af11\lang1023
<!-- An inline list is begun by <code>[</code> and terminated by <code>]</code>. Example: <code>listName=["a" [5 6] $b]; say $listName[0]</code> stores three Objects in a list named <code>listName</code> and prints <code>a</code>. Objects can be given custom identifiers for addressing them by separating them using <code>: </code>, in which case they should be additionally separated by <code>, </code>. Example: <code>listName=[foo: "a", bar: [5, 6], baz: b]; say $listName[foo]</code>.-->}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 }
\par \pard\plain \s35\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
String}
\par \pard\plain \s36\li567\ri0\lin567\rin0\fi0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
A string is a list of Dcs. Because all Dcs can be used in strings, any data type can be cast to a string, and all data types internally }{\cs19\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
are}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 strings of Dcs.}{
{\*\atnid }{\*\atnauthor }\chatn{\*\annotation{\*\atndate 1736006903}\ltrpar\rtlch \ltrch\loch{\langfe1023\alang1023\dbch\af11\dbch\af11\lang1023
An inline list is begun by <code>"</code> and terminated by a second <code>"</code>. In source form, <code>"</code> and <code>\\</code> must be escaped using <code>\\</code>. Example: <code>stringName="Hello, \\"World\\"!"</code> stores the string <code>Hello, "World"!</code> in a string named <code>stringName</code>. Strings can be concatenated by placing them beside each other: <code>a="foo"; b="baz"; say $a"bar"$b</code> prints <code>foobarbaz</code>.}}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 }
\par \pard\plain \s35\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Routine}
\par \pard\plain \s36\li567\ri0\lin567\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa283{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
A routine is a set of instructions for a computer to follow as part of the process of interpreting a document. Similar concepts are known as functions or subroutines in most programming languages, or as methods when used within objects. Routines have an associated structure that indicates what parameters may be passed to it.; they will be accessible through a list named }{\cs20\dbch\af6\dbch\af6\loch\f6\rtlch \ltrch\loch
!par}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
, and if named, then also through their names. Specifying a return type for a routine is optional. If none is specified, it will be treated as "void", meaning no return type is expected. It is denoted by }{\cs20\dbch\af6\dbch\af6\loch\f6\rtlch \ltrch\loch
()}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 followed by a block of statements, with its structure, if desired, within the parentheses. Example: }{\cs20\dbch\af6\dbch\af6\loch\f6\rtlch \ltrch\loch
String foo(String, String qux?, *)\{say $!par[1]$!par[2]$qux\}; foo("bar" "baz"); foo("bar" 6 "qux") # qux is 6, param 0 is bar, param 1 is 6, and param 2 is qux; foo(qux=6 "bar") # qux is still 6, but now parameter 0 is 6 and 1 is bar}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 represents an unnamed (positional-only) string parameter, an optional string parameter named "qux", and an unknown number (zero or more) of additional parameters of any type, and prints }
\par \pard\plain \s34\sb0\sa0\dbch\af6\dbch\af6\afs20\loch\f6\fs20\li567\ri0\lin567\rin0\fi0{\cs20\dbch\af6\dbch\af6\loch\f6\rtlch \ltrch\loch
bazbaz}
\par \pard\plain \s34\sb0\sa0\dbch\af6\dbch\af6\afs20\loch\f6\fs20\li567\ri0\lin567\rin0\fi0{\cs20\dbch\af6\dbch\af6\loch\f6\rtlch \ltrch\loch
6qux6}
\par \pard\plain \s34\sb0\sa0\dbch\af6\dbch\af6\afs20\loch\f6\fs20\li567\ri0\lin567\rin0\fi0\sb0\sa283{\cs20\dbch\af6\dbch\af6\loch\f6\rtlch \ltrch\loch
bar6}
\par \pard\plain \s36\li567\ri0\lin567\rin0\fi0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
. Because literals are printed by default when at the beginning of a statement, the "invoke" routine must be used to invoke a routine in some cases, such as when referencing a routine by a name stored in a variable or constant: }{\cs20\dbch\af6\dbch\af6\loch\f6\rtlch \ltrch\loch
a="I! Am! An! Awkward! Identifier!"; $a()\{say "blob"\}; invoke $a}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
. An alternative syntax for routine invocation, omitting parentheses, can be used if desired: }{\cs20\dbch\af6\dbch\af6\loch\f6\rtlch \ltrch\loch
foo(String, String qux?)\{\}; foo qux=6 bar}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
